Practical Lab 5 - Multivariate Regression, Non-Parametric Models and Cross-Validation¶

Problem Statement¶

The objective is to develop a multivariate polynomial regression, decision tree and KNN models, compare the models and find the best model that, in considering two features such as the body mass index (BMI),LTG in the dataset, can effectively forecast the risk of diabetes progression. This will assist doctors in identifying people who are at danger by serving as a screening tool.

Data Collection¶

Diabetes dataset is a small standard dataset available in scikit-learn. Diabetes dataset is collected by taking ten baseline features such as Age, Sex, Body Mass Index, average blood pressure, six blood serum measurements such as total serum cholestrol, LDL, HDL, Total cholestrol/HDL, LTG, blood sugar level from 442 patients and target which is a measure of diabetes progession one year after baseline. The 10 feature variables have been mean centered and scaled by the standard deviation times the square root of number of samples.

We will be importing the non-scaled dataset

Data Cleaning¶

I think there is no need for Data cleaning as the dataset does not contain any missing values and there is not such outliers. Instead of considering only one feature, we are going to consider two features such as BMI and LTG because it is closely correlated to the target variable and has a correlation coefficient in the range of 0.59 and 0.57 respectively.

Splitting the dataset into training and test dataset¶

In [150]:
# splitting the dataset into training(80%) and testing(20%) dataset
X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(df_diabetes_data[["bmi","s5"]], df_diabetes_data[["target"]], test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

Model Training¶

We have performed cross validation on 2 polynomial models of degree 1 and 2, decision trees of max depth 2 and 3, KNN models considering 5 and 6 nearest neighbors.

In [151]:
models = []
degrees = [1,2]
max_depth = [2,3]
n_neighbors = [5,6]
cross_val_scores = []
model_names = ["Polynomial Model Degree 1","Polynomial Model Degree 2","Decision Tree Depth 2","Decision Tree Depth 3","KNN - 5 neighbors","KNN - 6 neighbors"]

# Multivariate Polynomial models of degree 1 and 2
for deg in degrees:
    model = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(deg), LinearRegression())
    models.append(model)
# Decision Trees of depth 2 and 3
for depth in max_depth:
    model = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=depth)
    models.append(model)
# KNN of neighbors 5 and 6
for n in n_neighbors:
    model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n)
    models.append(model)

for index,model in enumerate(models):
    cross_val_results = cross_validate(model,X_train,y_train,cv = 5, scoring= ('r2', 'neg_mean_absolute_error','neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error'))
    Mean_R2 = np.mean(cross_val_results['test_r2'])
    Mean_MAE = np.mean(np.abs(cross_val_results['test_neg_mean_absolute_error']))
    SD_R2 = np.std(cross_val_results['test_r2'])
    SD_MAE = np.std(np.abs(cross_val_results['test_neg_mean_absolute_error']))
    Mean_MAPE = np.mean(np.abs(cross_val_results['test_neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error']))
    SD_MAPE = np.std(np.abs(cross_val_results['test_neg_mean_absolute_percentage_error']))
    cross_val_scores.append([model_names[index],Mean_R2,SD_R2,Mean_MAE,SD_MAE,Mean_MAPE,SD_MAPE])

Best Model Identification¶

From the cross validation results, it can be inferred that Mean R-squared value of 5 folds is higher for multivariate polynomial regression model of degree 1 when compared to decision trees and KNN models. It can be observed that the Mean R-squared value is negative for KNN models which implies that KNN model fails to fit the dataset. Also the Mean MAE is lower for Polynomial regression model of degree 1. So, the best model is Multivariate Polynomial Regression Model of degree 1.

Test data run on best model¶

In [154]:
# Multivariate polynomial regression model of Degree 1 is best model when compared to Decision trees and KNN
model = models[0]
model.fit(X_train,y_train)
test_r_square = r2_score(y_test,model.predict(X_test))
test_MAPE = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test,model.predict(X_test))
test_MAE = mean_absolute_error(y_test,model.predict(X_test))
print(f'R-squared value of Polynomial Regression of Degree 1 is {test_r_square:.2f}')
print(f'Mean Absolute Percentage error of Polynomial Regression of Degree 1 is {test_MAPE:.2f}')
print(f'Mean Absolute Error of Polynomial Regression of Degree 1 is {test_MAE:.2f}')

Conclusion¶

When considering features such as BMI and Low Tension Glucoma (LTG), Multivariate Polynomial regression model of degree 1 is able to explain only 28% of variability in diabetes progression in testing dataset. Polynomial regression model is able to predict target variable with 0.47% variations on average. This is somewhat acceptable when compared to the performance of KNN models which fails to fit the data completely.Next to polynomial regression model, Decision tree of maximum depth of 3 able to predict 46% of variability of target variable in training dataset.

Model Limitiations:¶

Polynomial regression models are capable of identifying the non-linear relationships but polynomial regression model of degree 1 assumes that linear relationship exits between dependent and independent variable but which is not the case with diabetes dataset. I think the model is facing underfitting issue.
